","5 May 1155":"5 mei 1155","1195":"1195","5 September 1195":"5 september 1195","1171":"1171","1235":"1235","5 July 1175":"5 juli 1175","1135":"1135","1134":"1134","1199":"1199","1155":"1155","about 1134":"circa 1134","about 1199":"circa 1199","Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hertfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, England","Bushey, Hertfordshire, England":"Bushey, Hertfordshire, England"},"en":{"about 1134–about 1199":"about 1134–about 1199","1135–1175":"1135–1175","1155–1195":"1155–1195","1171–1235":"1171–1235","1134–1199":"1134–1199","about 1171":"about 1171","1175":"1175","5 May 1155":"5 May 1155","1195":"1195","5 September 1195":"5 September 1195","1171":"1171","1235":"1235","5 July 1175":"5 July 1175","1135":"1135","1134":"1134","1199":"1199","1155":"1155","about 1134":"about 1134","about 1199":"about 1199","Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, England","Bushey, Hertfordshire, England":"Bushey, Hertfordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hereford","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Hertford (Hertfordshire) (in which the <i>t</i> was lost early, as in the modern pronunciation <i>Harford</i>), Hereford (Herefordshire), or Harford (Devon, Gloucestershire). The Devon and Herefordshire placenames derive from Old English <i>here</i> ‘army’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’, while the Gloucestershire and Hertfordshire placenames derive from Old English <i>heorot</i> ‘hart, stag’ + <i>ford</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Herford","meanings":["English: variant of   Hereford  .","German: variant of   Herfurth  .","German: habitational name from a place of that name in Westphalia."]},{"name":"Heryford","meanings":["Altered form of English   Hereford  ."]},{"name":"Heriford","meanings":["Altered form of English   Hereford  ."]},{"name":"Harford","meanings":["English (Wiltshire and Gloucestershire): variant of   Hereford  ."]},{"name":"Havard","meanings":["English and Welsh (Brecknockshire and Glamorgan): habitational name from Haverfordwest (Pembrokeshire), from Old English <i>hæfer</i> ‘goat’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’.","English and Welsh (Brecknockshire and Glamorgan): in some cases, the name may also be a variant of   Hereford  .","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Hahward</i>, composed of the elements <i>hah</i>, which is unexplained, and <i>ward</i> ‘guard’."]},{"name":"Hurford","meanings":["English (Devon and Somerset): variant of   Hereford  ."]}]},{"name":"Bertha","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of a Continental Germanic name, a short form of various compound women's personal names derived from <i>berht</i> ‘famous’ (akin to Modern English <i>bright</i>). It probably existed in England before the Conquest, and was certainly reinforced by Norman use, but fell out of use in the 15th century. It was reintroduced into the English-speaking world from Germany in the 19th century, but has once again gone out of fashion."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of the various boys' names with the first syllable <i>Ed-</i>, especially   Edward ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edward","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Bertha de Hereford was born about 1134, in Hertfordshire, England. She had at least 2 sons with Geoffrey Jarpenville I. She died about 1199, in her hometown, at the age of 67."},"et":{"about 1134–about 1199":"umbes 1134–umbes 1199","1135–1175":"1135–1175","1155–1195":"1155–1195","1171–1235":"1171–1235","1134–1199":"1134–1199","about 1171":"umbes 1171","1175":"1175","5 May 1155":"5. mai 1155","1195":"1195","5 September 1195":"5. september 1195","1171":"1171","1235":"1235","5 July 1175":"5. juuli 1175","1135":"1135","1134":"1134","1199":"1199","1155":"1155","about 1134":"umbes 1134","about 1199":"umbes 1199","Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hertfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, England","Bushey, Hertfordshire, England":"Bushey, Hertfordshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1134–about 1199":"noin 1134–noin 1199","1135–1175":"1135–1175","1155–1195":"1155–1195","1171–1235":"1171–1235","1134–1199":"1134–1199","about 1171":"noin 1171","1175":"1175","5 May 1155":"5. toukokuuta 1155","1195":"1195","5 September 1195":"5. syyskuuta 1195","1171":"1171","1235":"1235","5 July 1175":"5. heinäkuuta 1175","1135":"1135","1134":"1134","1199":"1